  "prompt": "What is the difference between \"don't we verb\" and \" do we not verb\"?",
  "response": "The phrases \"don't we verb\" and \"do we not verb\" essentially serve the same purpose in asking for confirmation but differ in tone and emphasis. Here\u2019s a breakdown of the differences:\n\n1. **Contraction vs. Full Form**:\n   - \"Don't we verb\" uses the contraction \"don't,\" which makes it sound more casual and conversational.\n   - \"Do we not verb\" uses the full form \"do we not,\" which can sound more formal or emphatic.\n\n2. **Tone and Emphasis**:\n   - \"Don't we verb\" can convey a sense of familiarity or shared understanding, often used in informal settings.\n   - \"Do we not verb\" may come across as more rhetorical or serious, potentially emphasizing doubt or confusion about a situation.\n\n3. **Context of Use**:\n   - \"Don't we verb\" is typically used in everyday conversation among friends or colleagues.\n   - \"Do we not verb\" might be used in more formal discussions, debates, or when someone wishes to highlight a point in a more intense manner.\n\n### Example:\n- \"Don't we need to leave soon?\" (Casual, seeking confirmation)\n- \"Do we not need to leave soon?\" (More formal, emphasizing the necessity)\n\nIn summary, while both phrases ask for confirmation, the choice between them can signal varying levels of formality and emotional tone.",
